     <h1>Typography with food</h1>
     <div class="text1">Mountains are massive, steep-sided landforms that rise significantly above their surroundings, typically featuring a distinct summit or peak. They are usually formed by tectonic plate collisions, volcanic activity, or erosion. Mountains cover one-fifth of Earth’s land surface, provide essential freshwater, and exist on all continents.</div>
     <div class="text2">"The Himalayas are among the oldest mountains."</div>
     <div class="text3">Formation: Mountains are primarily created by tectonic plate movements, including volcanic activity, folding, and faulting.</div>
     <p class="p1">Structure: A mountain has a base (bottom) and a summit or peak (top). A chain of mountains is called a range, and multiple, linked ranges form a mountain belt.</p>
     <p class="p2">Highest Peaks: Mount Everest in Asia is the highest mountain above sea level (8,848m). Mauna Kea in Hawaii is the tallest from base to summit, though mostly underwater. The highest mountain in the solar system is Olympus Mons on Mars.</p>
